<div  n='Din. 3' type='workDescription'>
	
<head ><bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0029.tlg003' type='cts-urn'>Din. 3</bibl></head>
<p >(<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Dinarchus</name>' <title >Against <name  type='person'>Demosthenes</name></title>; see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). This is a speech written by <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Dinarchus</name> for client (whose name we do not know) prosecuting <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Philocles</name> in a case involving bribery. In <date  when='-0324'>324 BCE</date>, <name  type='person'>Harpalus</name>, who was <name  type='person'>Alexander the Great</name>'s treasurer, fled from <placeName  key='Babylon'>Babylon</placeName> and came to <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> with a large amount of <name  type='person'>Alexander</name>'s money. He was admitted into the city, taken into custody with the money, but later escaped. Afterwards, it was found that several hundred talents was missing from the money he had brought to the city (see <term  sortKey='Money'>Money</term>). The <term  sortKey='Areopagus'>Areopagus</term> investigated the matter, and issued a report, or <term  sortKey='Apophasis'>apophasis</term> (<foreign  xml:lang='grc'>ἄποφασις</foreign>), saying that certain Athenians had accepted bribes from <name  type='person'>Harpalus</name>. The orator <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> was named in the report (see <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0029.tlg001' type='cts-urn'>Din. 1</bibl>. According to <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg063:3' type='cts-urn'>the Third Letter of <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name></bibl>, a work whose authenticity is doubtful, Philocles was convicted. Source: <bibl >Ian Worthington, <title >A Historical Commentary on Dinarchus: Rhetoric and Conspiracy in Late Fourth-Century Athens</title> (University of Michigan Press, Ann Arbor, 1992).</bibl></p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
